1
00:00:11,094 --> 00:00:13,931
-Dinner.
-Come... Hey, I've got an idea.

2
00:00:14,097 --> 00:00:16,058
Why don't you let me shoot that thing...

3
00:00:16,225 --> 00:00:20,187
...and you can go pick up the bloody, dead,
disgusting animal?

4
00:00:22,147 --> 00:00:23,815
-What?
-Try.

5
00:00:24,358 --> 00:00:27,319
Breathe. Everything breathe.

6
00:00:27,486 --> 00:00:30,280
Breathe. Aim.

7
00:00:31,448 --> 00:00:33,909
-Fire.
-Yeah.

8
00:00:37,496 --> 00:00:39,206
Aim that tree.

9
00:00:52,844 --> 00:00:54,763
Breathe.

10
00:01:00,769 --> 00:01:02,062
[SPEAKS IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

11
00:01:02,229 --> 00:01:05,482
-What does that mean?
-"You will die badly."

12
00:01:07,192 --> 00:01:08,777
Get.

13
00:01:34,177 --> 00:01:36,179
[OLIVER GROANING]

14
00:01:39,391 --> 00:01:42,561
Wait. Wait. You can't leave me here.
Don't do this to me. Please.

15
00:01:43,186 --> 00:01:44,646
[SCREAMS]

16
00:01:44,813 --> 00:01:48,233
Please! I didn't do anything!

17
00:01:48,400 --> 00:01:51,737
POLICEMAN 1: Stay back.
OLIVER: <i>The police think they know who I am.</i>

18
00:01:51,903 --> 00:01:53,363
<i>They think I'm the vigilante.</i>

19
00:01:53,530 --> 00:01:56,783
<i>The man in the hood,
terrorizing the city's criminals.</i>

20
00:01:56,950 --> 00:02:00,746
<i>They also think they have me trapped.
That I have no way out.</i>

21
00:02:01,288 --> 00:02:02,748
<i>They're only half-right.</i>

22
00:02:11,340 --> 00:02:14,259
OLIVER: This is a mistake.
-I'll be asking you a few questions.

23
00:02:14,426 --> 00:02:17,429
Standard stuff for the report.
Have you been arrested before?

24
00:02:17,596 --> 00:02:20,390
It's okay, I know the answer to that one.
Plenty of times.

25
00:02:20,557 --> 00:02:24,770
-Like I said, this is a mistake.
-As far as I can tell, the mistake I made...

26
00:02:24,936 --> 00:02:28,482
...was not shooting you down at the docks
when I had the chance.

27
00:02:28,649 --> 00:02:32,694
-I am not who you think I am.
-Oh, you're exactly who I think you are.

28
00:02:32,861 --> 00:02:35,364
You're a menace
who doesn't care about who he hurts.

29
00:02:35,530 --> 00:02:38,950
You're doing it with bows and arrows
instead of trust funds and yachts.

30
00:02:39,117 --> 00:02:43,664
Detective, you hate me. I get it.

31
00:02:43,830 --> 00:02:45,791
But that doesn't make me a vigilante.

32
00:02:45,957 --> 00:02:48,293
No, the security camera footage of you...

33
00:02:48,460 --> 00:02:51,254
...from the Unidac Auction
with the green hood does that.

34
00:02:51,421 --> 00:02:54,257
Again, I ran into the stairwell
once I heard shooting.

35
00:02:54,424 --> 00:02:59,429
I saw a duffle I thought maybe belonged
to the shooter, looked inside and saw...

36
00:02:59,596 --> 00:03:01,180
-...a hood.
-You took it home?

37
00:03:01,348 --> 00:03:03,684
We can't find it.
What about harassing Adam Hunt?

38
00:03:03,850 --> 00:03:05,977
Happened to take place
across the street...

39
00:03:06,144 --> 00:03:08,187
-...from your little bash.
-Coincidences.

40
00:03:08,355 --> 00:03:13,944
No. When they pile up like that,
it becomes evidence.

41
00:03:14,111 --> 00:03:15,904
-Parents are here.
-Tell them to wait.

42
00:03:16,071 --> 00:03:18,949
-I wanna see my son.
LANCE: I'm in the middle of an interrogation.

43
00:03:19,116 --> 00:03:22,703
Detective, I know you hate my family,
but I had no idea you'd go so far...

44
00:03:22,869 --> 00:03:25,247
...to arrest my son without any grounds.

45
00:03:25,414 --> 00:03:27,708
I have solid grounds,
and I have evidence.

46
00:03:27,874 --> 00:03:30,752
Which you can present
to Queen's attorney when he gets here.

47
00:03:30,919 --> 00:03:35,215
Until then, this interrogation
is over, detective.

48
00:03:37,843 --> 00:03:40,929
Sure. You have 15 minutes.

49
00:03:44,850 --> 00:03:47,519
Detective Lance appears to be
on some personal vendetta.

50
00:03:47,686 --> 00:03:49,563
He is.

51
00:03:49,730 --> 00:03:52,315
He blames me
for the death of his daughter.

52
00:03:53,150 --> 00:03:55,485
He also thinks
that I dress up in a green hood...

53
00:03:55,652 --> 00:03:59,322
-...and shoot people with arrows.
-Important thing is not to say anything...

54
00:03:59,489 --> 00:04:03,493
-...until your attorney gets here.
-Fine. I want Laurel.

55
00:04:03,660 --> 00:04:05,620
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

56
00:04:06,955 --> 00:04:10,917
Oliver, I don't think your ex-girlfriend
can be counted on to be objective here.

57
00:04:11,084 --> 00:04:15,338
She knows me better than anyone.
She knows that I could never be this guy.

58
00:04:15,505 --> 00:04:17,799
-Walter, you say Lance has a vendetta?
-Yes.

59
00:04:17,966 --> 00:04:20,552
I think Laurel can get him off of it.

60
00:04:21,178 --> 00:04:23,263
He raised her to do the right thing.

61
00:04:23,430 --> 00:04:25,766
That includes representing
an innocent man.

62
00:04:25,932 --> 00:04:27,851
So, Mom...

63
00:04:29,519 --> 00:04:31,938
...please.

64
00:04:35,484 --> 00:04:38,987
REPORTER: <i>Oliver Queen was arrested today
on suspicion of being the vigilante...</i>

65
00:04:39,154 --> 00:04:41,656
<i>...that has been targeting the wealthy
and corrupt.</i>

66
00:04:41,865 --> 00:04:43,784
Laurel.

67
00:04:43,950 --> 00:04:46,620
-Mrs. Queen, what...?
-It's Oliver. Something's happened.

68
00:04:46,787 --> 00:04:48,830
It's been all over the news.

69
00:04:49,289 --> 00:04:50,332
[SCOFFS]

70
00:04:50,499 --> 00:04:53,877
-These charges are ludicrous.
-I know.

71
00:04:54,669 --> 00:04:59,758
-Can I ask you, who's representing him?
-Well, that's why I'm here.

72
00:04:59,925 --> 00:05:02,677
He wants you to represent him.

73
00:05:02,886 --> 00:05:05,096
-Me?
-Yes. I told him it was a bad idea.

74
00:05:05,263 --> 00:05:07,682
But, to be frank, I am desperate.

75
00:05:07,891 --> 00:05:10,977
He says if you don't represent him,
he doesn't want any attorney.

76
00:05:11,144 --> 00:05:14,064
Mrs. Queen,
my father is the arresting officer.

77
00:05:14,231 --> 00:05:16,107
-Yes.
-I don't think it's a good idea...

78
00:05:16,274 --> 00:05:18,902
...for me to represent someone
I've been involved with.

79
00:05:19,486 --> 00:05:22,572
Listen, I am sorry for what your family
is going through...

80
00:05:22,739 --> 00:05:24,825
No. No apologies.

81
00:05:24,991 --> 00:05:29,913
Your idealism, I think, is why my son,
for all his mistakes, is so smitten with you.

82
00:05:32,499 --> 00:05:34,626
Regardless,
it was a bad idea on his part...

83
00:05:34,793 --> 00:05:38,421
...and I am sorry
if I made you feel uncomfortable.

84
00:05:44,094 --> 00:05:48,598
Docket ending 1-9-4-1,
<i>People v. Oliver Queen</i>.

85
00:05:48,765 --> 00:05:50,684
Murder, aggravated assault...

86
00:05:50,851 --> 00:05:54,938
...assault with intent,
menacing and trespassing.

87
00:05:58,984 --> 00:06:02,320
-Where's your attorney, Mr. Queen?
-I'm representing myself, judge.

88
00:06:02,487 --> 00:06:05,490
I'm not sure that's the wisest course,
Mr. Queen.

89
00:06:05,657 --> 00:06:07,993
I think it is.

90
00:06:08,159 --> 00:06:11,288
-I'm innocent.
-Then we'll consider that your plea.

91
00:06:11,454 --> 00:06:13,957
-Thank you.
-Now, as to bail.

92
00:06:14,124 --> 00:06:17,627
Your Honor, Mr. Queen's family
owns a pair of private jets.

93
00:06:17,794 --> 00:06:21,464
While on the subject of their wealth,
there is virtually no bail amount...

94
00:06:21,631 --> 00:06:23,800
...that could guarantee his presence
at trial.

95
00:06:23,967 --> 00:06:29,097
So then I guess it's a good thing
that the people's case is so circumstantial.

96
00:06:33,852 --> 00:06:38,106
Dinah Laurel Lance. I'd like to file my
appearance on behalf of the defendant.

97
00:06:39,149 --> 00:06:43,653
Mr. Queen's wealth should not deprive him
of the right to be released on bail...

98
00:06:43,820 --> 00:06:46,865
-...under the presumption of innocence.
-He is a flight risk.

99
00:06:47,032 --> 00:06:48,325
Then minimize the risk.

100
00:06:48,491 --> 00:06:53,371
The defendant is willing submit to home
confinement and electronic monitoring...

101
00:06:53,538 --> 00:06:57,042
...through the wearing of a UKG-45
administrated ankle device.

102
00:06:57,208 --> 00:06:58,585
-No, he wouldn't.
-Sold.

103
00:06:58,752 --> 00:07:01,630
-Your Honor...
-Bail is set at $15 million...

104
00:07:01,796 --> 00:07:03,089
...5 million dollars bond.

105
00:07:03,256 --> 00:07:08,053
Defendant to see Probation
for the fitting of a GPS device.

106
00:07:09,554 --> 00:07:12,015
I knew you couldn't resist saving my ass.

107
00:07:12,182 --> 00:07:16,227
-Gonna make me regret this, aren't you?
-No. It's gonna be like old times.

108
00:07:16,394 --> 00:07:20,065
Fortunately, with the legal case,
there's no way that you're this vigilante.

109
00:07:20,231 --> 00:07:23,318
-I agree.
-He's actually trying to make a difference.

110
00:07:23,526 --> 00:07:26,154
We both know that's not really your style.

111
00:07:33,370 --> 00:07:35,622
Mom, it's not that bad.

112
00:07:35,789 --> 00:07:38,458
Okay, this device has a direct line
into the precinct.

113
00:07:38,625 --> 00:07:41,920
You stay on the property, you're golden.
Any questions?

114
00:07:42,087 --> 00:07:44,881
I'm having a sizable get-together
here tomorrow evening...

115
00:07:45,048 --> 00:07:48,426
...and there is a likely chance
it spills into the outdoor pool.

116
00:07:48,593 --> 00:07:53,014
Pool deck's fine. Step on the grass, they're
sending a team to forcibly subdue you.

117
00:07:53,181 --> 00:07:55,225
WALTER: Thank you, officer.
OFFICER: Of course.

118
00:07:55,392 --> 00:07:59,187
-A sizable get together?
-I am confined for the foreseeable future.

119
00:07:59,354 --> 00:08:02,357
I might as well make the most of it.
Party is gonna be themed.

120
00:08:02,565 --> 00:08:04,818
I'm thinking prison.

121
00:08:04,985 --> 00:08:07,237
Burning Man meets
<i>Shawshank Redemption.</i>

122
00:08:07,404 --> 00:08:10,907
The invite says,
"Come before Oliver Queen gets off."

123
00:08:11,074 --> 00:08:14,828
Maybe a party's not in the best of taste,
considering the circumstances.

124
00:08:14,995 --> 00:08:18,832
Tommy, the circumstances are why
we're having the party in the first place.

125
00:08:18,999 --> 00:08:21,835
I want people to know I'm not worried
about any of this.

126
00:08:22,002 --> 00:08:24,004
Well, that makes one of us.

127
00:08:24,504 --> 00:08:26,339
LAUREL: Before you start yelling...
-Why yell?

128
00:08:26,506 --> 00:08:28,842
You're defending the man
that killed your sister.

129
00:08:29,009 --> 00:08:30,260
Oliver did not kill Sara.

130
00:08:30,427 --> 00:08:32,262
She wouldn't have been on that boat.

131
00:08:32,429 --> 00:08:35,348
Have you considered the possibility that
that's the reason...

132
00:08:35,515 --> 00:08:39,728
-...you're trying to make him this menace?
-It is the videotape, the suspicious timing.

133
00:08:39,894 --> 00:08:43,690
-That is the reason.
-This is Oliver Queen we're talking about.

134
00:08:43,857 --> 00:08:47,152
He wrecks fancy cars and he dates models.
He doesn't kill people.

135
00:08:47,360 --> 00:08:50,363
No, he just uses them. Like he used Sara.
And like he used you.

136
00:08:50,530 --> 00:08:52,949
He's only asked you to be his lawyer
to get at me.

137
00:08:53,116 --> 00:08:56,327
No, he asked me to be his lawyer
to get through to you.

138
00:08:56,494 --> 00:09:00,790
You hate the hood and you hate Oliver
and you want them to be the same person.

139
00:09:00,957 --> 00:09:05,503
But Oliver isn't the reason why Sara died
or the reason Mom left.

140
00:09:05,670 --> 00:09:07,172
I don't have to listen to this.

141
00:09:07,338 --> 00:09:09,007
And by the way...

142
00:09:11,134 --> 00:09:13,553
...you're not the only one
who misses them.

143
00:09:24,397 --> 00:09:25,482
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

144
00:09:25,648 --> 00:09:27,525
Yeah?

145
00:09:27,692 --> 00:09:30,361
Thank you for coming. Shut the door.

146
00:09:33,073 --> 00:09:35,909
Just a matter of time
before the police caught up with you.

147
00:09:36,076 --> 00:09:38,745
-Except they didn't.
-Oliver, they got you on video.

148
00:09:38,912 --> 00:09:41,247
I knew the camera was there,
I knew the police...

149
00:09:41,414 --> 00:09:45,293
...would review the footage and arrest me.
All part of the plan.

150
00:09:45,460 --> 00:09:46,961
So you wanted to get arrested?

151
00:09:47,170 --> 00:09:50,632
I returned to Starling City
and a few days later the vigilante appears.

152
00:09:50,799 --> 00:09:53,134
Somebody
was gonna make the connection.

153
00:09:53,301 --> 00:09:55,428
What part of serving yourself
to the cops...

154
00:09:55,595 --> 00:09:57,514
...will help you avoid going to prison?

155
00:09:58,264 --> 00:10:00,141
-There's more to it.
-There better be...

156
00:10:00,308 --> 00:10:02,519
...because your family is freaking out.

157
00:10:02,685 --> 00:10:05,355
Oliver, your mother and your sister
just got you back...

158
00:10:05,522 --> 00:10:08,066
...and now you're gonna put them
through a trial?

159
00:10:08,233 --> 00:10:11,569
-Don't you care?
-Of course I care.

160
00:10:12,362 --> 00:10:14,781
The mission comes first.

161
00:10:17,617 --> 00:10:19,327
Who is he?

162
00:10:19,911 --> 00:10:20,995
Leo Mueller.

163
00:10:21,204 --> 00:10:26,543
German arms dealer, suspected in the theft
of 100 M2-49 squad automatic weapons.

164
00:10:26,709 --> 00:10:29,045
-Okay.
-Last night he arrived in Starling City...

165
00:10:29,212 --> 00:10:30,296
...to sell the guns.

166
00:10:30,463 --> 00:10:34,509
Don't you imagine there's enough trouble
you're in than to go after this guy?

167
00:10:34,717 --> 00:10:37,804
I imagine what would happen if a gang
got military hardware.

168
00:10:37,971 --> 00:10:41,391
I imagine our city's streets
turned into a war zone.

169
00:10:41,558 --> 00:10:45,979
But you're under house arrest, Oliver,
which means you can't go after this guy.

170
00:10:46,521 --> 00:10:49,899
Look. For now, I would just like you
to shadow Mueller.

171
00:10:50,066 --> 00:10:52,318
I would like you to track his movements.

172
00:10:52,485 --> 00:10:55,071
I wanna know where the buy
is happening.

173
00:10:55,989 --> 00:10:58,032
Okay.

174
00:10:58,491 --> 00:11:03,329
-And how am I supposed to track him?
-Well, you know us billionaire vigilantes.

175
00:11:03,997 --> 00:11:05,540
We do love our toys.

176
00:11:07,750 --> 00:11:09,752
[ELECTRICITY HUMMING]

177
00:11:13,089 --> 00:11:14,174
Wow.

178
00:11:24,267 --> 00:11:25,684
Ow.

179
00:11:28,980 --> 00:11:30,689
Whoo.

180
00:11:34,944 --> 00:11:36,487
[BEEPING]

181
00:11:36,654 --> 00:11:38,907
Oh, that's sweet.

182
00:11:40,992 --> 00:11:44,621
-You wanted to see me, sir?
-No, I didn't.

183
00:11:45,788 --> 00:11:49,334
In fact, this meeting isn't taking place.

184
00:11:52,795 --> 00:11:56,299
How long have you been head of Security
at Queen Consolidated, Josiah?

185
00:11:56,466 --> 00:12:00,428
-Going on seven years now, sir.
-Sounds about right.

186
00:12:01,054 --> 00:12:05,975
But what I'm about to tell you
will test the bounds of your discretion.

187
00:12:06,142 --> 00:12:09,979
You're aware of the <i>Queen's Gambit?</i>
Robert Queen's ill-fated yacht?

188
00:12:11,231 --> 00:12:12,357
I found it.

189
00:12:12,523 --> 00:12:16,069
Sir, the boat went down
in the North China Sea five years ago.

190
00:12:16,236 --> 00:12:19,989
Which is why my discovery
of its remains in a warehouse downtown...

191
00:12:20,156 --> 00:12:22,033
...was unexpected, to say the least.

192
00:12:23,326 --> 00:12:26,704
I want you to transfer those remains
to a secure location.

193
00:12:26,871 --> 00:12:28,206
Can I count on you?

194
00:12:29,707 --> 00:12:31,167
[CHUCKLES]

195
00:12:31,334 --> 00:12:32,460
What's going on, sir?

196
00:12:32,627 --> 00:12:36,172
That's very much
what I'm trying to determine.

197
00:12:47,475 --> 00:12:48,935
Thank you both for coming.

198
00:12:49,102 --> 00:12:52,355
Thank you.
It's nice to get out of the house.

199
00:12:52,522 --> 00:12:58,319
I'll cut right to it. Detective Lance arrested
your client without consulting my office.

200
00:12:58,486 --> 00:13:02,115
So, congratulations,
I am willing to consider a plea in this case.

201
00:13:02,282 --> 00:13:03,366
Absolutely not.

202
00:13:03,533 --> 00:13:05,660
SPENCER:
Mr. Queen spent five years in seclusion...

203
00:13:05,868 --> 00:13:08,871
...on a deserted island,
cut off from civilization.

204
00:13:09,038 --> 00:13:12,917
It is quite possible he's suffering
from some form of post-traumatic stress.

205
00:13:13,084 --> 00:13:16,629
Given that,
we would support a plea of insanity...

206
00:13:16,795 --> 00:13:21,384
...conditional on a period of indeterminate
incarceration at a psychiatric facility.

207
00:13:22,176 --> 00:13:25,804
-No, thank you. I'm not crazy.
-Finally something we agree on.

208
00:13:25,972 --> 00:13:28,891
-He's not a nut. He's a killing machine.
-I'm neither.

209
00:13:29,058 --> 00:13:32,186
There is nothing you can say
that I would believe.

210
00:13:34,605 --> 00:13:36,399
I'll take a polygraph.

211
00:13:36,899 --> 00:13:39,277
-Polygraphs are inadmissible.
-In front of a jury.

212
00:13:39,444 --> 00:13:41,696
I'll talk a polygraph in front of him.

213
00:13:42,780 --> 00:13:44,365
He's the one I need to convince.

214
00:13:46,784 --> 00:13:48,036
I'm gonna need a minute.

215
00:14:02,050 --> 00:14:05,803
You're looking at life in prison.
What Spencer just offered you is a gift.

216
00:14:05,970 --> 00:14:10,767
I'm not crazy. I am innocent.
I kind of wanna take the polygraph...

217
00:14:10,975 --> 00:14:17,523
...and if I take it and I fail,
then I will consider making a deal.

218
00:14:18,232 --> 00:14:19,984
Fine.

219
00:14:20,777 --> 00:14:24,322
I'll set up the poly. And I will tell Spencer
that we're not pleading out.

220
00:14:24,489 --> 00:14:29,160
But, Oliver? You have a family. Friends.
People who actually care about you.

221
00:14:29,327 --> 00:14:33,748
So don't for one second think you're the
only person with something to lose here.

222
00:14:36,876 --> 00:14:38,628
I'll be right back.

223
00:15:00,566 --> 00:15:01,734
[GROANS]

224
00:15:03,694 --> 00:15:07,365
Please. Sit. You're making me feel rude.

225
00:15:15,873 --> 00:15:19,794
I do apologize
for my men's treatment of you.

226
00:15:20,628 --> 00:15:21,796
They're...

227
00:15:21,963 --> 00:15:26,843
They're trained to view any stranger
as hostile.

228
00:15:30,263 --> 00:15:32,098
I'm Edward Fyers, by the way.

229
00:15:35,977 --> 00:15:37,562
And you are?

230
00:15:39,647 --> 00:15:41,732
I'm Oliver Queen.

231
00:15:43,317 --> 00:15:48,573
I was shipwrecked here.
I don't know for how long.

232
00:15:49,949 --> 00:15:53,244
My family has money, lots of money.

233
00:15:53,411 --> 00:15:54,871
You would be...

234
00:15:55,079 --> 00:15:58,708
You'd be really well compensated
for my rescue.

235
00:15:58,875 --> 00:16:02,545
Well, I look forward to that.

236
00:16:02,712 --> 00:16:04,714
But for the moment, let's just talk.

237
00:16:04,881 --> 00:16:06,591
About what?

238
00:16:06,757 --> 00:16:08,968
Well, for instance...

239
00:16:12,430 --> 00:16:13,764
...this gentleman.

240
00:16:15,016 --> 00:16:16,767
Do you know him?

241
00:16:23,608 --> 00:16:24,901
-No.
-No?

242
00:16:25,109 --> 00:16:29,530
-No. Who's he?
-You're a poor liar.

243
00:16:36,162 --> 00:16:37,455
I've been polite.

244
00:16:38,623 --> 00:16:42,043
I'll offer you one more chance
before my manners leave me.

245
00:16:42,210 --> 00:16:45,546
Hey. Hey. I don't know this guy.

246
00:16:45,713 --> 00:16:48,216
I... I thought I was on this island
all by myself.

247
00:16:49,175 --> 00:16:51,594
Do you know what this island is named?

248
00:16:51,761 --> 00:16:55,848
We're on Lian Yu.
Mandarin for "purgatory."

249
00:16:56,015 --> 00:16:58,392
But I can make it feel like hell.

250
00:17:01,938 --> 00:17:03,898
I don't know why you're protecting him.

251
00:17:05,358 --> 00:17:07,151
You're young. Foolish.

252
00:17:08,361 --> 00:17:10,863
Perhaps you don't know why either.

253
00:17:13,032 --> 00:17:15,743
Think on that
when you're begging for death.

254
00:17:19,705 --> 00:17:21,457
He's yours now.

255
00:17:37,473 --> 00:17:40,810
Hey, Speedy. One of the workers left a keg
too far from the bar.

256
00:17:40,977 --> 00:17:44,689
Can you ask them to move it? Please?
I got the ankle thingy.

257
00:17:45,398 --> 00:17:47,358
I don't want to set off a SWAT invasion.

258
00:17:50,403 --> 00:17:56,450
Hey, all this stuff, it's gonna be fine.
I promise.

259
00:17:56,617 --> 00:17:58,953
Yeah, well, when you and Dad left
on the yacht...

260
00:17:59,120 --> 00:18:03,165
...you promised me I'd see you
in a few days, which didn't happen.

261
00:18:03,332 --> 00:18:06,752
This is different than that.
I didn't do any of this stuff.

262
00:18:06,919 --> 00:18:10,131
You know that. Right?

263
00:18:10,298 --> 00:18:12,925
You're out all the time.

264
00:18:13,092 --> 00:18:17,054
You have those scars, and since you've
been back, you've been acting really weird.

265
00:18:17,221 --> 00:18:20,474
None of this makes me
some Robin Hood wannabe.

266
00:18:22,018 --> 00:18:25,396
And you gave me this.
I mean, it's an arrowhead.

267
00:18:26,480 --> 00:18:28,649
Oh, man.

268
00:18:31,152 --> 00:18:34,822
Thea, I bought that in the gift shop
of the Beijing Airport.

269
00:18:40,870 --> 00:18:46,334
Now I'm sort of happy I didn't buy you
the shot glass with the panda on it...

270
00:18:46,500 --> 00:18:49,837
...because then you'd be worried
I was Panda Man.

271
00:18:52,089 --> 00:18:56,427
You know,
I knew you couldn't be this person.

272
00:18:56,594 --> 00:19:00,848
I just... I can't lose you again.

273
00:19:02,808 --> 00:19:04,310
Deal.

274
00:19:08,397 --> 00:19:10,816
Moira, thank you for coming
on such short notice.

275
00:19:10,983 --> 00:19:14,987
Yes. Could you please make this quick.
I'm in the midst of a family emergency.

276
00:19:15,154 --> 00:19:17,782
Yes, of course.
It's all over the local news.

277
00:19:17,948 --> 00:19:20,242
Possibly even national.

278
00:19:20,409 --> 00:19:22,495
-Well, I know what you're thinking.
-Do you?

279
00:19:22,662 --> 00:19:26,540
My son is not the man targeting the list.
The charges are preposterous.

280
00:19:26,707 --> 00:19:29,877
Not according to the district attorney,
assistant attorney...

281
00:19:30,044 --> 00:19:33,172
...the investigating detective
and the police that filed charges.

282
00:19:33,339 --> 00:19:36,550
-That detective has a vendetta.
-Why?

283
00:19:37,593 --> 00:19:39,804
Is there something untoward
about your family?

284
00:19:42,223 --> 00:19:45,351
If so, something really needs
to be done about that.

285
00:19:46,227 --> 00:19:48,062
LANCE:
Is your name Oliver Queen?

286
00:19:48,229 --> 00:19:51,065
You don't know who I am, detective?

287
00:19:52,191 --> 00:19:54,068
The questions calibrate the polygraph.

288
00:19:54,235 --> 00:19:55,945
-Is your name Oliver Queen?
-Yes.

289
00:19:56,112 --> 00:19:59,240
Were you born in Starling City,
May 16th, 1985?

290
00:19:59,407 --> 00:20:00,616
Yes.

291
00:20:00,825 --> 00:20:02,410
-Is your hair blue?
-No.

292
00:20:02,576 --> 00:20:04,412
Ever been to Iron Heights prison?

293
00:20:05,621 --> 00:20:07,164
No.

294
00:20:11,836 --> 00:20:14,088
Are you the man in this picture?

295
00:20:15,047 --> 00:20:18,217
Where can I find the man in this picture?

296
00:20:19,885 --> 00:20:21,178
No.

297
00:20:30,062 --> 00:20:33,274
-You steal $40 million off Adam Hunt?
-No, I didn't.

298
00:20:33,441 --> 00:20:35,693
Were you marooned on an island
for five years?

299
00:20:35,860 --> 00:20:36,986
-Yes.
-Is that relevant?

300
00:20:37,153 --> 00:20:40,364
Since you asked, whatever happened
to your client on that island...

301
00:20:40,531 --> 00:20:43,367
...turned him into a cold-blooded killer.

302
00:20:47,371 --> 00:20:49,915
[SCREAMING]

303
00:20:50,416 --> 00:20:54,378
The physician reported that 20 percent
of your body is covered in scar tissue.

304
00:20:54,545 --> 00:20:58,716
[SCREAMING]

305
00:21:00,134 --> 00:21:02,470
The machine won't work
unless you ask a question.

306
00:21:02,636 --> 00:21:04,054
Did that happen to you there?

307
00:21:04,889 --> 00:21:05,973
Yes.

308
00:21:06,140 --> 00:21:10,186
When you came back, you told everyone
that you were alone on that island.

309
00:21:10,895 --> 00:21:14,231
Are you claiming that your scars
were self-inflicted?

310
00:21:15,149 --> 00:21:16,859
No.

311
00:21:17,026 --> 00:21:20,529
I wasn't alone. I didn't wanna talk
about what happened on the island.

312
00:21:20,696 --> 00:21:23,741
-Why not?
-The people that were there tortured me.

313
00:21:25,326 --> 00:21:27,119
Have you killed anyone?

314
00:21:37,338 --> 00:21:38,923
Yes.

315
00:21:43,219 --> 00:21:46,931
When I asked your daughter Sara
to come on my father's yacht with me.

316
00:21:51,101 --> 00:21:53,270
I killed your daughter.

317
00:22:09,286 --> 00:22:13,123
I'd have to study the data,
but just eyeballing it, he's telling the truth.

318
00:22:13,290 --> 00:22:14,458
Hmm.

319
00:22:15,459 --> 00:22:17,795
Can I assume you'll be recommending
Ms. Spencer...

320
00:22:17,962 --> 00:22:19,964
...to drop all charges against my client?

321
00:22:20,130 --> 00:22:23,592
No. I know a guilty man when I see one.
He is guilty.

322
00:22:24,093 --> 00:22:25,886
Whether you can see it or not.

323
00:22:30,307 --> 00:22:32,893
[3OH!3'S "YOU'RE GONNA LOVE THIS"
PLAYING FROM SPEAKER]

324
00:22:51,495 --> 00:22:52,621
[MUSIC STOPS]

325
00:22:52,788 --> 00:22:54,915
-Hi, everybody.
ALL: Hey.

326
00:22:55,082 --> 00:23:00,963
I'm very touched that you came to celebrate
with me before I am sent up the river.

327
00:23:01,130 --> 00:23:04,967
Closest neighbors are 6 miles away,
so don't worry about the noise.

328
00:23:05,134 --> 00:23:07,428
Actually, on second thought...

329
00:23:08,262 --> 00:23:10,639
...let's wake those losers up!

330
00:23:10,806 --> 00:23:12,224
[MUSIC RESUMES PLAYING]

331
00:23:12,433 --> 00:23:13,976
[ALL CHEERING]

332
00:23:18,647 --> 00:23:22,735
If you think this is what prison's like,
you are in for a rude awakening.

333
00:23:23,485 --> 00:23:27,156
Mueller's car's been in the warehouse
district of the Glades for 45 minutes.

334
00:23:27,323 --> 00:23:29,491
Yeah, it's a good place for an arms deal.

335
00:23:29,658 --> 00:23:32,161
Okay, since it's going down tonight,
what do we do?

336
00:23:32,328 --> 00:23:35,998
-Drop a dime on Mueller with the cops?
-No. The man in the hood...

337
00:23:36,540 --> 00:23:38,000
...he's gonna stop them.

338
00:23:38,167 --> 00:23:40,336
Oliver, you can't leave the house.

339
00:23:40,502 --> 00:23:44,298
It doesn't have to be me in the hood.

340
00:23:48,385 --> 00:23:51,180
That's why you threw
this ridiculous party?

341
00:23:51,805 --> 00:23:54,099
A hundred witnesses placing you
at the house...

342
00:23:54,266 --> 00:23:56,602
...while I'm across town
dressed as a vigilante?

343
00:23:56,769 --> 00:24:00,147
I thought it was gonna be enough
just for you to be seen in the hood.

344
00:24:00,314 --> 00:24:03,984
I didn't count on Mueller showing up,
and the possibility that the Glades...

345
00:24:04,151 --> 00:24:07,363
...could be flooded with machine guns.

346
00:24:08,614 --> 00:24:10,366
Look...

347
00:24:11,575 --> 00:24:16,497
...I promise, it was never my intention
to put you in harm's way.

348
00:24:16,664 --> 00:24:20,626
Oliver, I didn't think joining your crusade
was ever gonna be risk-free.

349
00:24:20,793 --> 00:24:23,671
I just don't like being played.

350
00:24:24,462 --> 00:24:26,799
You have gotten used to lying
to everyone else...

351
00:24:26,966 --> 00:24:29,467
...but I'm the one guy you don't lie to.

352
00:24:31,595 --> 00:24:33,138
You're right.

353
00:24:33,806 --> 00:24:35,057
I'm sorry.

354
00:24:40,354 --> 00:24:41,479
So am I going to jail?

355
00:24:45,734 --> 00:24:47,653
No, man.

356
00:24:49,363 --> 00:24:51,448
I gotta stop an arms deal.

357
00:24:56,494 --> 00:24:57,913
[PHONE RINGING]

358
00:25:00,082 --> 00:25:01,875
-Hello?
VOGEL: <i>Mr. Steele.</i>

359
00:25:02,084 --> 00:25:06,380
<i>I'm sorry to bother you, sir.
This is Mike Vogel down in Security.</i>

360
00:25:06,588 --> 00:25:08,549
<i>I have some sad news for you.</i>

361
00:25:08,716 --> 00:25:11,010
<i>The company's head of Security,
Josiah Hudson...</i>

362
00:25:11,176 --> 00:25:13,095
<i>...was in a car accident tonight.</i>

363
00:25:13,262 --> 00:25:15,389
<i>He's dead, sir.</i>

364
00:25:17,391 --> 00:25:20,394
[DANCE MUSIC PLAYING FROM SPEAKER]

365
00:25:23,605 --> 00:25:24,982
OLIVER:
Hello.

366
00:25:25,149 --> 00:25:28,819
Do we have a legal meeting or something?
Because I have friends over.

367
00:25:31,321 --> 00:25:33,615
Do you think maybe
you can tear yourself away...

368
00:25:33,782 --> 00:25:37,786
...from this inappropriately themed rave
for a couple minutes?

369
00:25:41,665 --> 00:25:43,042
LAUREL:
Wow.

370
00:25:44,168 --> 00:25:47,004
I can't remember the last time
that I've been in this room.

371
00:25:47,171 --> 00:25:52,550
I can. Halloween 2005.
We were getting ready for Tommy's party.

372
00:25:52,718 --> 00:25:57,431
Ah. Yes, I wore those horrible fishnets.

373
00:25:58,682 --> 00:26:00,017
I thought you looked good.

374
00:26:02,478 --> 00:26:04,438
Listen...

375
00:26:04,897 --> 00:26:06,982
...I just wanted to come by
and apologize...

376
00:26:07,149 --> 00:26:10,360
...for my father's behavior today
during the polygraph.

377
00:26:10,861 --> 00:26:15,699
You don't have to apologize for him.
He has a right to feel any way that he wants.

378
00:26:15,866 --> 00:26:18,576
It wasn't just Sara, Ollie.

379
00:26:19,661 --> 00:26:21,330
What do you mean?

380
00:26:21,705 --> 00:26:26,794
After Sara died,
my father threw himself into his work.

381
00:26:26,960 --> 00:26:30,172
I think that's part of the reason
I'm an attorney.

382
00:26:30,506 --> 00:26:33,801
He ran to the law and I followed.

383
00:26:33,967 --> 00:26:35,344
But my mother couldn't.

384
00:26:38,097 --> 00:26:39,597
So she left him.

385
00:26:41,975 --> 00:26:44,186
Left us.

386
00:26:45,437 --> 00:26:49,274
Look, I'm not trying to tell you this
to make you feel bad or worse.

387
00:26:49,441 --> 00:26:52,319
I just... I really want you
to understand him.

388
00:26:55,364 --> 00:26:57,699
Why don't you hate me?

389
00:26:59,118 --> 00:27:00,452
You should.

390
00:27:02,620 --> 00:27:04,373
I did.

391
00:27:05,415 --> 00:27:08,460
For so long, I did, Ollie.

392
00:27:09,253 --> 00:27:12,297
But after today, I realized...

393
00:27:12,506 --> 00:27:15,050
...I was so focused
on what happened to my family...

394
00:27:15,217 --> 00:27:19,388
...that I didn't even stop and wonder
what could have happened to you.

395
00:27:24,059 --> 00:27:28,939
I didn't know about the torture
or your scars.

396
00:27:31,608 --> 00:27:35,946
What happened to you on that island
was far more than you deserved.

397
00:27:39,783 --> 00:27:44,037
And I was wrong
that I didn't ask you before.

398
00:27:44,246 --> 00:27:47,916
But I'm asking you now.
I need to know. I need to see.

399
00:27:48,458 --> 00:27:49,543
Are you sure?

400
00:27:51,962 --> 00:27:53,839
Yes.

401
00:28:12,774 --> 00:28:14,692
How did you survive this?

402
00:28:14,860 --> 00:28:17,529
There were times when I wanted to die.

403
00:28:18,989 --> 00:28:20,657
In the end...

404
00:28:22,492 --> 00:28:25,120
...there was something I wanted more.

405
00:28:49,519 --> 00:28:52,731
You don't... Laurel, you don't have to go.

406
00:28:56,818 --> 00:29:00,656
Amazing. You have resolve
I didn't credit you for.

407
00:29:03,116 --> 00:29:06,119
Or perhaps
he truly doesn't know anything.

408
00:29:06,328 --> 00:29:07,955
Yes.

409
00:29:08,664 --> 00:29:10,457
You should put him out of his misery.

410
00:29:55,711 --> 00:29:57,379
[MUELLER SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

411
00:29:58,463 --> 00:30:01,008
MUELLER:
The M249 machine gun.

412
00:30:01,508 --> 00:30:07,055
Gas-powered, air-cooled,
fires up to 800 rounds per minute.

413
00:30:09,224 --> 00:30:10,225
[WHISTLES]

414
00:30:13,228 --> 00:30:15,731
We need to move. Now.

415
00:30:16,398 --> 00:30:17,399
[YELLS IN GERMAN]

416
00:30:17,566 --> 00:30:18,650
Go. Come on.

417
00:30:18,817 --> 00:30:20,235
Let's go.

418
00:30:38,003 --> 00:30:41,465
Well, I'm not accustomed
to being summoned to the office...

419
00:30:41,631 --> 00:30:43,925
...in the middle of the night.

420
00:30:45,969 --> 00:30:49,473
Well, what was it that was so important
that I had to race down here?

421
00:30:51,016 --> 00:30:53,852
I found the <i>Queen's Gambit</i>, Moira.

422
00:30:56,646 --> 00:30:59,566
I know you secretly
had the boat salvaged.

423
00:30:59,733 --> 00:31:03,236
I wanted to move it to a secure location
before confronting you about it.

424
00:31:03,445 --> 00:31:08,325
In fact, I sent Josiah Hudson to
the warehouse for precisely that purpose...

425
00:31:08,658 --> 00:31:12,537
...but he died mysteriously
in a car accident.

426
00:31:13,163 --> 00:31:17,292
I hope you now have a better understanding
of why it is I've been so distant of late.

427
00:31:17,459 --> 00:31:21,380
It's very disconcerting to discover the
person with whom you share your home...

428
00:31:21,546 --> 00:31:25,342
...your bed and your heart,
has been lying to you so convincingly.

429
00:31:25,509 --> 00:31:29,179
I would be a fool not to consider
all the things you have told me were lies.

430
00:31:29,346 --> 00:31:31,890
-Walter, you're my husband.
-Yes, I am.

431
00:31:33,767 --> 00:31:35,268
Walter, please.

432
00:31:35,477 --> 00:31:38,480
You've got to stop looking into this.
It's not safe.

433
00:31:38,647 --> 00:31:43,527
You'll be... You'll be upsetting people.
People with influence.

434
00:31:44,403 --> 00:31:46,613
You are very far out of your depth.

435
00:31:51,535 --> 00:31:53,662
[PHONE RINGS]

436
00:31:54,579 --> 00:31:57,666
DIGGLE:
<i>Man in the hood, 1. Gang bangers, zero.</i>

437
00:31:57,833 --> 00:31:58,834
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

438
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:01,002
Hang on. Yeah?

439
00:32:01,503 --> 00:32:04,005
Mr. Queen, if you're entertaining guests
upstairs...

440
00:32:04,172 --> 00:32:07,008
-...should I have drinks sent up?
OLIVER: No, it's just me here...

441
00:32:07,175 --> 00:32:09,386
...and I'm on my way back down.

442
00:32:09,928 --> 00:32:12,514
Good job. Now get back here.

443
00:32:40,041 --> 00:32:42,586
LANCE:
Yeah. Yeah.

444
00:32:44,045 --> 00:32:45,714
How did you know I was in trouble?

445
00:32:45,881 --> 00:32:48,717
When the guy was fighting you,
he broke the ankle monitor.

446
00:32:48,884 --> 00:32:50,719
MOIRA: Are you all right?
-I'm fine.

447
00:32:50,886 --> 00:32:54,181
-Oliver.
-Mom, I promise.

448
00:32:54,681 --> 00:32:58,602
This is on you. By accusing my son
publicly, you've made him a target.

449
00:32:58,768 --> 00:33:01,563
WALTER: Do you have any idea
who attacked Oliver?

450
00:33:01,730 --> 00:33:06,276
We haven't identified him. It must be
someone with a grudge against the hood.

451
00:33:06,985 --> 00:33:09,779
-What are you doing?
-Just got a call from my lieutenant.

452
00:33:11,198 --> 00:33:14,326
An arms dealer was attacked
across town tonight.

453
00:33:16,453 --> 00:33:19,206
By the vigilante.
Multiple witnesses put him there.

454
00:33:19,789 --> 00:33:22,626
In light of that, all charges against your son
are dropped.

455
00:33:22,792 --> 00:33:25,921
I'm truly sorry for what's happened
to your family, Quentin.

456
00:33:27,130 --> 00:33:30,342
But would you kindly get the hell out
of my house?

457
00:33:37,641 --> 00:33:39,476
OLIVER:
Mr. Lance?

458
00:33:42,270 --> 00:33:43,522
Thank you.

459
00:33:58,745 --> 00:34:00,956
Moira. Did we have an appointment?

460
00:34:01,122 --> 00:34:05,502
No. But I decided to screw propriety
after you tried to have my son killed.

461
00:34:07,003 --> 00:34:10,131
I'm sure you understand
I was justified in suspecting your son...

462
00:34:10,298 --> 00:34:12,759
...of being the vigilante
targeting our associates.

463
00:34:12,926 --> 00:34:14,803
I had to take steps.

464
00:34:14,970 --> 00:34:17,722
And now that you know
your steps were taken in error?

465
00:34:17,889 --> 00:34:19,724
That Oliver is not your enemy?

466
00:34:20,350 --> 00:34:21,726
[CHUCKLES]

467
00:34:21,893 --> 00:34:25,146
I offer my sincerest apologies.

468
00:34:27,482 --> 00:34:30,318
I know you found out
I had the yacht salvaged.

469
00:34:30,485 --> 00:34:33,905
Just as I know
you had Josiah Hudson killed.

470
00:34:34,990 --> 00:34:39,160
Well, accidents tend to befall people
who are too curious.

471
00:34:40,412 --> 00:34:42,956
I've been the good soldier.

472
00:34:43,373 --> 00:34:46,835
I've done everything you asked.

473
00:34:47,502 --> 00:34:52,007
But if any member of my family
so much as gets a paper cut...

474
00:34:52,173 --> 00:34:56,303
...I will burn your entire world to ashes.

475
00:35:11,610 --> 00:35:13,528
[GROANING]

476
00:35:14,738 --> 00:35:18,575
I tell you, island dangerous.
But you not tell them where to find me.

477
00:35:19,117 --> 00:35:21,119
You stronger than I thought.

478
00:35:21,286 --> 00:35:23,371
Take it. I lead them off. You stay.

479
00:35:24,914 --> 00:35:28,793
Remember, everything breathe.
You breathe, you survive here longer.

480
00:35:30,337 --> 00:35:31,588
I'm coming with you.

481
00:35:35,717 --> 00:35:37,552
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

482
00:35:40,513 --> 00:35:43,099
-Rough party.
-My father told me what happened.

483
00:35:44,893 --> 00:35:48,104
-Are you okay?
-Yeah, I'm fine.

484
00:35:51,775 --> 00:35:53,735
These are your polygraph results.

485
00:35:54,653 --> 00:35:58,323
My father asked you
if you'd ever been to Iron Heights.

486
00:35:58,573 --> 00:36:01,576
It's the prison where the vigilante saved me
last week.

487
00:36:02,160 --> 00:36:05,163
It's also where you and I went
on our eighth-grade field trip.

488
00:36:06,998 --> 00:36:09,292
When you said
that you had never been there...

489
00:36:09,459 --> 00:36:13,505
...I thought maybe you were just nervous,
or that you'd forgotten.

490
00:36:15,340 --> 00:36:18,051
But then I looked at your results...

491
00:36:18,635 --> 00:36:22,180
...and there is a slight flutter in your answer
to that question.

492
00:36:23,682 --> 00:36:26,434
And if you lied on one,
you could have lied on others.

493
00:36:26,601 --> 00:36:31,481
What happened to me being too selfish
to be a masked crusader?

494
00:36:31,648 --> 00:36:34,401
Oliver, I saw your scars.

495
00:36:41,783 --> 00:36:45,704
Do you wanna know why I don't talk
about what happened to me there?

496
00:36:47,831 --> 00:36:49,290
Because, if people knew...

497
00:36:50,333 --> 00:36:51,626
...if you knew...

498
00:36:54,087 --> 00:36:56,506
...you'd see me differently.

499
00:36:57,382 --> 00:37:01,136
And not as some vigilante guy.

500
00:37:04,514 --> 00:37:06,224
As damaged.

501
00:37:07,851 --> 00:37:09,310
I don't sleep.

502
00:37:10,937 --> 00:37:12,313
I barely eat.

503
00:37:13,189 --> 00:37:15,108
I can barely sign my name...

504
00:37:17,402 --> 00:37:20,321
...let alone aim a bow and arrow.

505
00:37:23,825 --> 00:37:26,161
After last night...

506
00:37:29,122 --> 00:37:32,417
...clearly we're still attracted
to one another.

507
00:37:36,463 --> 00:37:38,339
Oliver...

508
00:37:39,132 --> 00:37:42,677
...nothing can ever happen between us.

509
00:37:45,013 --> 00:37:46,765
I know.

510
00:38:02,572 --> 00:38:03,823
DIGGLE:
<i>So you lied to her.</i>

511
00:38:03,990 --> 00:38:06,367
Or maybe you just gave her
a version of the truth.

512
00:38:06,534 --> 00:38:09,329
I told her what she needed to hear.
She was too close.

513
00:38:09,829 --> 00:38:11,039
DIGGLE:
The sad thing is...

514
00:38:11,206 --> 00:38:13,416
...I think you actually believe that.

515
00:38:13,583 --> 00:38:16,503
<i>I think things didn't go down exactly
as you planned.</i>

516
00:38:16,669 --> 00:38:19,506
<i>You didn't count on so many people
having questions.</i>

517
00:38:19,672 --> 00:38:21,341
<i>Doubting you.</i>

518
00:38:21,508 --> 00:38:24,260
<i>You didn't think about what happens
when you lie.</i>

519
00:38:24,427 --> 00:38:26,012
-Thank you, Chris.
-Walter?

520
00:38:26,179 --> 00:38:28,348
DIGGLE:
<i>Especially when you lie to ones you love most.</i>

521
00:38:28,515 --> 00:38:30,141
What is this?

522
00:38:30,475 --> 00:38:31,559
Business trip.

523
00:38:32,685 --> 00:38:36,940
I decided it's long overdue for me
to inspect our holdings in Melbourne.

524
00:38:37,649 --> 00:38:39,442
And how long will you be?

525
00:38:40,568 --> 00:38:42,487
I don't know.

526
00:38:48,660 --> 00:38:50,954
DIGGLE:
<i>When you were stuck on that island...</i>

527
00:38:51,120 --> 00:38:53,289
<i>...plotting your grand plan to save the city...</i>

528
00:38:53,456 --> 00:38:56,042
<i>...I don't think you stopped
to consider the effect...</i>

529
00:38:56,209 --> 00:38:58,962
<i>...it would have on the people in your life.</i>

530
00:39:02,549 --> 00:39:04,509
Let's go.

531
00:39:05,176 --> 00:39:06,803
LANCE: It's fine.
LAUREL: You're okay.

532
00:39:06,970 --> 00:39:09,430
No, no, no. Put it...

533
00:39:10,348 --> 00:39:11,933
Or how it might hurt them.

534
00:39:13,184 --> 00:39:14,936
You're wrong.

535
00:39:16,479 --> 00:39:19,107
I think about it all the time.

536
00:39:20,233 --> 00:39:23,486
And just to be clear,
not being able to tell my family the truth...

537
00:39:27,031 --> 00:39:30,285
...it doesn't hurt anyone worse
than it hurts me.

538
00:39:32,996 --> 00:39:36,124
-Where you going?
-Mueller still has guns. I have to stop him.

539
00:39:36,291 --> 00:39:39,210
-Oliver.
-He had his chance.

540
00:39:39,377 --> 00:39:45,758
MUELLER: Twenty-eight crates, four guns
in each crate, $250,000 cash.

541
00:39:47,135 --> 00:39:49,137
Take it or leave it.

542
00:39:49,304 --> 00:39:51,180
That's the deal.

543
00:39:52,515 --> 00:39:53,850
MAN:
Yeah, okay.

544
00:40:02,817 --> 00:40:04,402
[GRUNTS]

545
00:40:10,867 --> 00:40:12,535
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

546
00:40:20,877 --> 00:40:25,131
Leo Mueller, you have failed this city.

547
00:40:25,298 --> 00:40:26,883
[MUELLER SCREAMS]

